(11393, 'Ky-mani Marley', 'http://www.indievox.com/kymanimarley', 'http://cdn2-data.indievox.com/indievox_user/30000/11393/pix/11393180X180.jpg?1427770998', 3, 'Following in the legacy of his father''s footsteps, Ky-Mani Marley continues on with the pop-reggae sound for which his family is known. Stepping into his Jamaican roots, Marley independently released his debut, The Journey, in 1998. It developed a huge following on the reggae charts as well as some dedication from fans of Bob Marley. The following year, The Journey was eventually re-released in the United States. Many More Records appeared in spring 2001, with Radio following in 2007. Both were released on Artists Only.'),
(11395, 'Madvillain', 'http://www.indievox.com/madvillain', 'http://cdn1-data.indievox.com/indievox_user/30000/11395/pix/11395180X180.jpg?1427770998', 2, 'Madvillain is the moniker and stage name for the underground hip-hop collaboration between MF DOOM (MC) and Madlib (producer). \r\n\r\nTheir debut album Madvillainy was met with critical acclaim for its unique approach - short songs, obscure lyrics, few choruses and a sound which was generally unfriendly to commercial radio. This was directly opposite to the formulas of popular hip hop of the time. The album features a host of guests from stones throw including MED, Wildchild and Doom/Madlib aliases Viktor Vaughn and Quasimoto respectively.\r\n\r\nAn instrumental version of the album and two remix EPs from Madvillainy were released on Stones Throw. Remixes were by Four Tet and Koushik.'),
